                    Answers to Logikbots SQL Course at
                    https://www.logikbot.com/courses/the-fundamentals-of-transact-sql-for-machine-learning-engineers


Question 1 
Write a SELECT statement that lists the customers along with their ID numbers. Include the last names, first names, and company names.

Answer
SELECT 
	CustomerID,
	FirstName,
	LastName,
	CompanyName
FROM SalesLT.Customer


Question 2
Write a SELECT statement that lists the name, product number, and color of each product.

Answer
SELECT
	Name,
	ProductNumber,
	Color
FROM SalesLT.Product


Question 3
Write a SELECT statement that lists the customer ID numbers and sales order ID numbers from the SalesLT.SalesOrderHeader table

Answer
SELECT
	SalesOrderID,
	CustomerID
FROM SalesLT.SalesOrderHeader


Question 4
**** Need to use the AdventureWorks 2019 database
Write a query using a WHERE clause that displays all the employees listed in the HumanResources.
Employee table who have the job title Research and Development Engineer. 
Display the business entity ID number, the login ID, and the title for each one.

Answer
SELECT
	BusinessEntityID, 
	LoginID,
	JobTitle
FROM HumanResources.Employee
WHERE JobTitle = 'Research and Development Engineer'


Question 5
Write a query using a WHERE clause that displays all the names in Person.Person with the middle name J. 
Display the first, last, and middle names along with the ID numbers.

Answer
SELECT
	FirstName,
	LastName,
	MiddleName,
	BusinessEntityID
FROM Person.Person
WHERE MiddleName = 'J'


Question 6
Write a query displaying all the columns of the Production.ProductCostHistory table from the rows that were modified on June 17, 2003.

Answer
// Will not return any values
SELECT
	ProductID,
	StartDate,
	EndDate,
	StandardCost,
	ModifiedDate
FROM Production.ProductCostHistory
WHERE ModifiedDate = '2013-06-17'


Question 7
Rewrite the query you wrote in question 1, changing it so that the employees who do not have the title Research and Development Engineer are displayed

Answer
// Question 1 in this case refers to question 1 using the 2019 database
// There is no difference between using != and <> for not equal
// <> is however ANSI standard
SELECT
	BusinessEntityID, 
	LoginID,
	JobTitle
FROM HumanResources.Employee
WHERE JobTitle <> 'Research and Development Engineer'
